"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 1 Chronicles chapter 6
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-1chronicles-6-6.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/1chronicles.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/1chronicles.json

Key classification decisions:
- Aaronide priestly succession (vv1-15): type → Christ as eternal high priest (Heb 4-10)
- Phinehas covenant (v4): type → Christ's permanent, inviolable priesthood (Heb 7:24)
- Zadok (v13): shadow → Christ's Melchizedek-order priesthood supersedes the Levitical
- Jehozadak into exile (v15): shadow → removal/return of the one who makes atonement
- Temple musicians (vv31-48): theme → Christ as focus of all worship; Heb 2:12 applied
- Aaronic atonement monopoly (v49): type → Christ's once-for-all atonement (Heb 9-10)
- Levitical cities (vv54-81): shadow → transcended by the church as dwelling of God
- Cities of refuge (vv57, 67, 76): type of Christ as refuge (Heb 6:18)
- Genealogical connectors: revelation of God or theme with brief entries
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>The Levitical genealogy opens with YHWH's set-apart tribe. A revelation of God: the Levites had no territorial inheritance — 'I am your portion and your inheritance' (Num 18:20). In this the Levites are the earliest embodiment of the principle Christ extends: the people of God are defined not by land or bloodline but by direct relationship with YHWH. The NT applies Levitical language to all believers — 'a royal priesthood, a holy nation' (1 Pet 2:9) — making every Christian spiritually Levite, set apart for God as portion.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Kohath is listed first because the Aaronide priestly line runs through him. The Kohathite clan carried the most sacred tabernacle objects in the wilderness — the ark, lampstand, table, and altars. As a type, the Kohathite system of mediated access anticipates Christ's mediatorial role: 'there is one mediator between God and men, the man Christ Jesus' (1 Tim 2:5), who gives permanent access to the divine presence that the Kohathites could only temporarily and carefully carry.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Aaron, Moses, and Miriam — the founding trio of the exodus (Mic 6:4); Aaron's four sons follow, two of whom died for offering unauthorized worship. As a type, the contrast between the sons whose offering was rejected (Nadab and Abihu) and the line that continued (Eleazar and Ithamar) foreshadows the distinction between worship offered on human terms and worship accepted by God. Christ is the one whose self-offering was perfectly accepted — 'he offered himself without blemish to God' (Heb 9:14) — inaugurating the worship that replaces the Aaronic system.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Eleazar begot Phinehas, who received 'a covenant of a perpetual priesthood' (Num 25:10-13) for his zeal in stopping apostasy. As a type, the Phinehas covenant establishes the principle that the priesthood is maintained by covenant faithfulness and divine grant, not hereditary right alone. Christ holds 'his priesthood permanently, because he continues forever' (Heb 7:24) — not a renewed Phinehas covenant but an eternal appointment that makes the Phinehas covenant a shadow: the priesthood-by-covenant finds its fulfillment in the priest-who-is-the-covenant.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Abishua son of Phinehas continues the covenant priesthood line. A theme of generational faithfulness: YHWH's commitment to the priestly line is maintained generation by generation, revealing a God whose covenant-keeping spans centuries. The NT presents this as the ground for confidence in Christ: 'Jesus Christ is the same yesterday and today and forever' (Heb 13:8), the permanently faithful covenant-keeper in whom all generational promises find their anchor and terminus.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Bukki son of Abishua — the chain continues. The unbroken priestly succession through the period of the judges is a revelation of God's covenant faithfulness: despite Israel's cyclical apostasy, YHWH maintained the priestly structure. This faithfulness reaches its climax in Christ, who comes 'when the fullness of time had come' (Gal 4:4) — not despite human failure but through the covenant structure YHWH maintained in its midst. The Levitical chain is one visible expression of that sustained commitment.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Uzzi son of Bukki — the succession continues through the period of disputed priesthood. A revelation of God: he preserves the priestly institution even through human division and institutional competition. As Christ is 'able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him' (Heb 7:25), God's preservation of the priestly chain through Uzzi's generation reveals the divine determination to maintain the means of atonement — a determination Christ permanently fulfills.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Zerahiah son of Uzzi — bridging wilderness to monarchy. A theme of covenant continuity: the same God who called Levi, appointed Aaron, and established Phinehas maintains the priestly line through the centuries. This long-range faithfulness is the ground of the NT's appeal: 'he who promised is faithful' (Heb 10:23). The priestly succession is one of the OT's most concrete demonstrations of that faithfulness, leading to the one who fulfills and ends the system.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Meraioth son of Zerahiah — the final link before the monarchy. The schematic four names covering perhaps 400 years reveals that the Chronicler's purpose is covenant certification, not biography. A revelation of God: his purposes are not frustrated by historical obscurity. As Paul writes, 'the gifts and calling of God are irrevocable' (Rom 11:29) — the priestly line, and ultimately Christ through that line, cannot be annulled by the absence of detailed records.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Azariah served as priest in the temple Solomon built — the Aaronic priesthood at the height of the Davidic-Solomonic kingdom. A shadow: the simultaneous operation of priest and king at the dedicated sanctuary represents the OT's best approximation of what Christ alone fully is. Christ unites these permanently: he is 'a priest forever' (Heb 7:17) and 'King of kings' (Rev 19:16) — the two offices that Israel could only approximate separately are combined inseparably in him.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Amariah son of Azariah — the succession through the monarchy. A theme: the priestly line endured as Israelite kings rose and fell. In Christ, the vulnerability of divided institutions is permanently resolved: he combines both offices in one person who cannot be displaced. 'He holds his priesthood permanently' (Heb 7:24) and 'his kingdom will have no end' (Luke 1:33) — what the Aaronide succession and the Davidic dynasty imperfectly and separately maintained, Christ secures together and forever.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Ahitub son of Amariah — another link in the Zadokite chain. A revelation of God: the covenant of atonement operated independently of Israel's political fortunes, never fully collapsing even when the monarchy descended into apostasy. This divine preservation of the means of atonement reveals that the covenant of grace is more durable than any political institution — and ultimately reaches its goal in Christ, who 'offered for all time a single sacrifice for sins' (Heb 10:12), making the institution permanent by making it once-for-all.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Zadok son of Ahitub — founder of the Zadokite priesthood dominant for centuries; Ezekiel reserved the inner sanctuary for his sons (Ezek 44:15-16). As a shadow pointing to what supersedes it: Hebrews argues that a change of priesthood was necessary — 'if perfection had been attainable through the Levitical priesthood... what further need would there have been for another priest to arise after the order of Melchizedek?' (Heb 7:11). Christ is not a Zadokite but a Melchizedek-order priest (Ps 110:4; Heb 7:15-17) — a designation that exposes the entire Zadokite system as penultimate, pointing beyond itself to the one who was 'holy, innocent, unstained, separated from sinners' (Heb 7:26).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Shallum son of Zadok — the Zadokite succession moving toward the monarchy's end. A theme: the priesthood outlasting institutions. Kings would fall, the temple would be destroyed — but the priestly succession would continue through exile and restoration. This institutional resilience foreshadows the resurrection principle: Christ's priesthood is established 'by the power of an indestructible life' (Heb 7:16), incapable of being ended by any historical catastrophe, including his own death.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Jehozadak went into exile when the LORD sent Judah and Jerusalem into captivity by the hand of Nebuchadnezzar. A shadow of profound weight: the high priest — the one who makes atonement for all Israel — is removed from the sanctuary and carried away by the destroyer. This shadow finds its deepest fulfillment in the crucifixion, where the one who makes atonement is removed from the holy city and killed outside its walls (Heb 13:12: 'Jesus also suffered outside the gate'). But as Jehozadak's son Joshua returned to rebuild the sanctuary, so the exiled Priest rose to minister 'in the greater and more perfect tabernacle' (Heb 9:11). The priestly pattern of exile-and-return reaches its fulfillment in death-and-resurrection.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The three Levitical clans are re-introduced in full. A theme: together the three clans constitute the full Levitical community — no single family alone carries the whole weight of worship. In Christ, this distributed system is replaced by a single High Priest who 'always lives to make intercession' (Heb 7:25), concentrating in himself what was spread across three clans, their sub-families, and multiple service roles. He is not one priest among others but the one in whom all priestly functions converge.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The sons of Gershom — Libni and Shimei — founded the Gershomite clans responsible for carrying the tent curtains and screens. A revelation of God: the divine order for worship involves carefully differentiated roles within a unified community. Christ fulfills this ordering principle by himself bearing every function — prophet, priest, and king — that the OT distributed across offices, tribes, and families. He is not merely one member of the Levitical community but the one in whom the entire community's diversity of service finds its singular ground.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The sons of Kohath include Izhar, from whose line came Korah the rebel (Num 16). The Korahite sons who did not die (Num 26:11) became temple singers whose psalms are preserved in the Psalter. A revelation of God's grace: even the descendants of those who rebelled against the appointed mediators were rehabilitated into the worship community. In Christ, this principle is universalized: those who crucified the Son of David are invited to repentance and inclusion (Acts 2:36-38). There is no ancestral rebellion that forecloses welcome to the community of worship.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The sons of Merari — Mahli and Mushi — carriers of the tabernacle's structural components, the heaviest parts of the sanctuary. A theme: the Merarites carried what was unglamorous — frames, bars, pillars — without which the sanctuary could not stand. Christ's work similarly includes what is unglamorous: 'he humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death, even death on a cross' (Phil 2:8). The structural weight that makes the permanent sanctuary possible is borne by the Son who himself becomes the foundation: 'no one can lay a foundation other than that which is laid, which is Jesus Christ' (1 Cor 3:11).</p>",
    "20": "<p>Gershom's line continues: Libni → Jahath → Zimmah. A theme of sustained faithfulness through obscure generations: most individuals in the Levitical genealogy made no great mark on Israel's history; their faithfulness consisted in maintaining their assigned role generation by generation. This theme of faithful obscurity is one Christ elevates: 'whoever would be great among you must be your servant' (Matt 20:26). The Levitical genealogy honors ordinary faithfulness with its own kind of memorial — names preserved in covenant history.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Joah → Iddo → Zerah → Jeatherai — the Gershomite succession continues. A revelation of God: YHWH maintains his purposes through the long, patient work of generational faithfulness rather than spectacular intervention at every turn. This divine patience is presented in the NT as expressing his salvific will: 'The Lord is not slow to fulfill his promise as some count slowness, but is patient toward you, not wishing that any should perish' (2 Pet 3:9). The Levitical succession is a concrete historical expression of that patience.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The Korahite line: Amminadab, Korah, Assir. As noted at v18, Korah's descendants survived and served as temple musicians. A shadow pointing to Christ's redemptive work: even the descendants of those who rebelled against Moses and Aaron were welcomed into the worship community. In Christ, the principle is universalized — 'Christ Jesus came into the world to save sinners' (1 Tim 1:15), and the rebel's descendants have a place in the new-covenant choir.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Elkanah, Ebiasaph, Assir — the Korahite succession. Ebiasaph survived the earth's opening (Num 16:32; 26:11) and became an ancestor of temple gatekeepers. A theme: survival through judgment leading to renewed service is the pattern of resurrection. As Ebiasaph's family continued in service after Korah's judgment, so Christ's community 'walks in newness of life' (Rom 6:4) after participating in his death. The gatekeepers' descendance from Korah's survivors is a living type of resurrection-service.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Tahath, Uriel, Uzziah, Shaul — Kohathite succession. Uriel is appointed by David for the ark-bringing procession (1 Chr 15:5), connecting genealogy to historical appointment. A revelation of God: he works through named, specific persons appointed for specific sacred tasks — not anonymous forces but designated individuals. Christ is the supreme named individual: 'there is salvation in no one else, for there is no other name under heaven given among men by which we must be saved' (Acts 4:12).</p>",
    "25": "<p>The sons of Elkanah: Amasai and Ahimoth — a branch-point. The Levitical genealogy includes both the famous (Samuel, Heman) and the undistinguished. In God's purposes, both kinds of names matter; the messianic line in Matthew 1 includes both the recognized (David, Solomon) and the obscure (Abiud, Eliakim, Azor). A revelation of God: he works through ordinary faithfulness as readily as through famous achievement, because his purposes depend on his own faithfulness rather than human notoriety.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Elkanah, Zophai, Nahath — the Kohathite line approaching Samuel's generation. A revelation of God: the line that will produce Samuel runs through multiple ordinary generations without recorded distinction. The great prophet is not a spontaneous miracle but the culmination of generations of covenant faithfulness. Similarly, Christ arrives 'when the fullness of time had come' (Gal 4:4) — at the culmination of a long genealogical and covenantal preparation that ran through many undistinguished generations.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Eliab, Jeroham, Elkanah — Samuel's father. The Chronicler identifies Samuel as a Kohathite Levite, establishing his priestly identity. A shadow pointing to Christ: Samuel integrates prophetic and priestly functions in one person — anointing kings (1 Sam 10:1; 16:13), offering sacrifice (1 Sam 7:9), interceding for Israel (1 Sam 7:5). This prophetic-priestly integration in Samuel is the OT's closest approximation of what Christ is permanently: prophet, priest, and the one whose intercession never fails.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The sons of Samuel: Joel and Abiah, whose corruption prompted the demand for a king (1 Sam 8:1-5). A shadow: the failure of Samuel's house to maintain covenant faithfulness drove the narrative toward the divine King who would not fail. The failure of Joel and Abiah led to David; David's covenant led to Christ. The very corruption of the priestly-judicial institution points to the need for the one who is 'the same yesterday and today and forever' (Heb 13:8) — whose faithfulness depends not on his sons but on his own eternal nature.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The sons of Merari: Mahli, Libni, Shimei, Uzzah. The narrative Uzzah died touching the ark (1 Chr 13:9-10), illustrating that holiness cannot be approached casually even by those with hereditary proximity. A revelation of God: this holiness is not abolished in Christ but mediated through him — 'our God is a consuming fire' (Heb 12:29), yet 'let us draw near with confidence to the throne of grace' (Heb 4:16). The same holiness that killed Uzzah is approached through Christ's perfect mediation.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Shimea, Haggiah, Asaiah — the Merarite line ends with Asaiah appointed for the ark-bringing procession (1 Chr 15:6, 11). A revelation of God: he maintained the Merarite line through obscurity and appointed Asaiah to a specific historical role at the appointed time. This pattern — preparation through faithfulness, appointment at the appointed moment — is the pattern of the incarnation: 'when the fullness of time had come, God sent forth his Son' (Gal 4:4), prepared through centuries of covenant history for his specific historical appointment.</p>",
    "31": "<p>David appointed the singers 'after the ark had found its resting place.' A shadow: worship organized around the settled presence of God in the sanctuary. The ark's resting place is the shadow; Christ is the antitype — 'in him the whole fullness of deity dwells bodily' (Col 2:9), and all Christian worship is organized around his permanent presence. As the ark's settlement prompted the musical appointment, so Christ's enthronement (Acts 2:33-36) released the Spirit who enables 'psalms and hymns and spiritual songs' (Eph 5:19) — worship for the new-covenant resting place of divine presence.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The singers served before the tabernacle until Solomon built the temple; they served 'according to their prescribed order.' A theme: worship maintained continuously from temporary tent to permanent temple. The continuity is theologically important — there was no gap. In Christ, the transition from temple to new-covenant worship is equally continuous: Jesus says 'salvation is from the Jews' (John 4:22) while announcing worship 'in spirit and truth.' The form changes; the continuity of worship directed toward the living God is unbroken across the transition.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Heman the singer, son of Joel, son of Samuel — Samuel's grandson leads the temple choir. A type with remarkable depth: Heb 2:12 applies Ps 22:22 ('I will proclaim your name to my brothers; in the midst of the congregation I will sing your praise') to Christ himself. Christ is the one in whom the prophetic and the liturgical converge absolutely: he is both the word proclaimed and the voice of praise. Heman integrating Samuel's prophetic legacy with temple music is the OT's approximation; Christ is its fulfillment — the ultimate choir director, leading the congregation's praise in the new-covenant assembly.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The son of Joel, the son of Elkanah — Heman's ancestry through Samuel's corrupt son Joel shows that the musical ministry is not destroyed by leaders' failures. A revelation of God: YHWH works through and beyond moral failure to accomplish his purposes. The same principle operates in Christ's genealogy — 'David the king begat Solomon by her that had been the wife of Uriah' (Matt 1:6 KJV) — where adultery and murder are in the Messiah's ancestral line, yet he arrives as 'the Holy One of God' (Mark 1:24). God's purposes cannot be thwarted by the sins of intermediate generations.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The son of Mahath, the son of Amasai — Heman's ancestry traced deeper into the Kohathite line. A theme: those who lead Israel's worship are not newcomers but persons shaped by generations of covenant formation. Christ's own genealogical depth exceeds all: 'before Abraham was, I am' (John 8:58) — yet he entered the genealogical stream ('descended from David according to the flesh,' Rom 1:3) to lead worship from within the covenant community.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The son of Elkanah, the son of Joel — repeated names across generations reflecting continuous covenant identity. A revelation of God: the same names recur because the same God is trusted by each generation. This continuity of trust across generations is what Heb 11 celebrates — 'these all died in faith, not having received the things promised' (Heb 11:13) — and what Christ brings to completion: 'Jesus, the founder and perfecter of our faith' (Heb 12:2), in whom the long inter-generational trust finally reaches its object.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The son of Azariah, the son of Zephaniah — the ancestry moves toward the founding Kohathite genealogy. A theme: many carried the most exalted theophoric names (Zephaniah = 'YHWH has treasured') in roles of continuity and transition rather than individual distinction. Christ honors those whose service is unseen: 'your Father who sees in secret will reward you' (Matt 6:6). The Levitical genealogy's inclusion of these otherwise unknown names is itself a form of that heavenly recognition.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The son of Tahath, the son of Assir, the son of Ebiasaph, the son of Korah — Heman's ancestry reaches the rebel. A revelation of God's grace: the worship-music that fills the Psalter flows from a family that survived divine judgment on their ancestor. God's grace is deeper than ancestral guilt. Christ's atoning work is the ultimate expression of this principle — he 'descended into the lower parts of the earth' (Eph 4:9), entering the place of judgment to bring life out of it.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Asaph stood at Heman's right hand — director of the twelve Asaphite psalms (Ps 50; 73-83), which range from theophanic praise to theodicy to communal lament. A type pointing to Christ: Heb 2:12 applies Ps 22:22 to Christ leading the congregation's praise. The Son of God is the ultimate choir director — not merely inspiring the Asaphite guild but personally leading the new-covenant assembly's praise. Asaph's cross-clan service alongside Heman (Gershomite alongside Kohathite) also anticipates the gathering of diverse peoples in Christ's one body.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The son of Michael, the son of Baaseiah — Asaph's Gershomite ancestry. Asaph is from a different Levitical clan (Gershom) than Heman (Kohath), yet they serve together in the same worship ministry. A shadow of the new-covenant community: 'there is neither Jew nor Greek' (Gal 3:28) — different streams of origin united in worship. This cross-clan collaboration in temple music prefigures the gathering of 'every tribe and language and people and nation' (Rev 5:9) around the Lamb.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The son of Malchijah, the son of Ethni, the son of Zerah — Asaph's Gershomite line. A revelation of God: YHWH's purposes in worship include persons from diverse backgrounds contributing distinct but complementary gifts. The NT develops this as the body metaphor: 'the body does not consist of one member but of many' (1 Cor 12:14). The Levitical differentiation of roles — three clans, multiple families, distinct functions — is the OT prototype of the charismatic diversity of the body of Christ.</p>",
    "42": "<p>The son of Adaiah, the son of Ethan, the son of Zimmah — the Gershomite ancestry approaches the wilderness generation. A theme: the worship ministry of Solomon's temple has roots reaching to the founding Levitical community of the wilderness. In Christ, worship has roots even deeper — 'before the foundation of the world' (Eph 1:4; Rev 13:8). The temple choir's deep genealogical roots are a shadow of the eternal ground of Christian worship in the one who existed before all creation.</p>",
    "43": "<p>The son of Shimei, the son of Jahath, the son of Gershom, the son of Levi — Asaph's ancestry certified all the way to Levi himself. A revelation of God: genealogical certification into the covenant community requires a documented ancestry. In Christ, this certification is given to every believer through adoption rather than genealogy: 'you have received the Spirit of adoption as sons, by whom we cry, &#8216;Abba! Father!&#8217;' (Rom 8:15). The Levitical genealogical certification becomes available to all through the Spirit's witness to adoption in Christ.</p>",
    "44": "<p>Ethan the Merarite stood at the left — likely connected to Psalm 89 ('A Maskil of Ethan the Ezrahite'), which ends with the lament: 'Lord, where is your steadfast love of old?' (Ps 89:49). A type with prophetic weight: Ethan's guild produced the psalm that most directly confronts the apparent failure of the Davidic covenant. The answer comes in the NT: 'I will give you the holy and sure blessings of David' (Acts 13:34, citing Isa 55:3), applied to the risen Jesus — Christ's resurrection is YHWH's answer to the Ethanite lament. The choir director who voiced the deepest question finds his answer in the resurrection of the Son of David.</p>",
    "45": "<p>The son of Hashabiah, the son of Amaziah, the son of Hilkiah — Ethan's Merarite ancestry. A theme: the ordinary chain of succession through which extraordinary worship is eventually produced. Ethan's lament-psalm that wrestles with covenant failure came from a family with no recorded distinction in these intermediate generations. A revelation of God: YHWH raises up those who will give voice to the community's deepest questions through the same patient, generational process by which he raises up all his servants and, ultimately, his Son.</p>",
    "46": "<p>The son of Amzi, the son of Bani, the son of Shemer — the Merarite chain continues. Shemer ('preserved one') is an evocative name within a genealogy whose function is to certify preserved covenant identity. Christ is the ultimate preserver: 'I give them eternal life, and they will never perish, and no one will snatch them out of my hand' (John 10:28). The genealogical preservation the Chronicler documents is a temporal echo of the eternal preservation Christ secures for those in his hand.</p>",
    "47": "<p>The son of Mahli, the son of Mushi, the son of Merari, the son of Levi — Ethan's ancestry traced to Merari and Levi. The three music directors — Heman/Kohath, Asaph/Gershom, Ethan/Merari — together represent all of Levi in the temple's worship leadership. A shadow pointing to Christ in whom all of Israel's offices and functions are concentrated: prophet, priest, king, and now all three Levitical traditions find their focus in the one who is 'the same yesterday and today and forever' (Heb 13:8).</p>",
    "48": "<p>Their kinsmen the Levites were appointed for all the service of the tabernacle — all remaining Levitical roles beyond the three directors. A revelation of God: YHWH's worship requires full-service participation from his people; no single role covers everything. In Christ, this distributed service is intensified — 'to each is given the manifestation of the Spirit for the common good' (1 Cor 12:7). The full range of temple service roles becomes in the NT the full range of spiritual gifts, each assigned by the same Spirit to different members of Christ's body for God's worship and the community's upbuilding.</p>",
    "49": "<p>Aaron and his sons alone were responsible for the altar and for making atonement. As a type: this is the chapter's most direct Christological pointer. The Aaronic monopoly on sacrifice and atonement structurally anticipates Christ's unique atoning work. As only Aaron's sons could offer on the altar — 'the outsider who comes near shall be put to death' (Num 3:10) — so only Christ makes the definitive atonement: 'he entered once for all into the holy places... by means of his own blood, thus securing an eternal redemption' (Heb 9:12). The Aaronic monopoly is not arbitrary exclusiveness but a shadow of the uniqueness of Christ's mediation: there is no other sacrifice, no other priest, no other means of atonement.</p>",
    "50": "<p>The sons of Aaron — Eleazar, Phinehas, Abishua — recapitulating the priestly succession. The repetition connects the Aaronic role (v49) to the Aaronic ancestry: authority to offer atonement belongs to this specific identified line. As a type, the insistence on specific ancestry for the atoning priest foreshadows the NT's insistence on Christ's specific, historical identity: 'descended from David according to the flesh' (Rom 1:3), 'born of woman, born under the law' (Gal 4:4). Atonement requires a specific, authorized, historically identified person — not a principle but the Person.</p>",
    "51": "<p>Bukki, Uzzi, Zerahiah — the Aaronide recapitulation continues. A theme: the repetition of the priestly list emphasizes the non-negotiable connection between atonement function and specific genealogical authorization. The NT concentrates this in Christ: 'there is one God, and there is one mediator between God and men, the man Christ Jesus' (1 Tim 2:5). The Aaronic specificity is the OT form of the NT's claim to exclusive mediation — both resist the idea that any and all mediators are equivalent before God.</p>",
    "52": "<p>Meraioth, Amariah, Ahitub — the succession approaching the monarchy. A revelation of God: the priestly function is maintained through politically turbulent times. This divine maintenance of the means of atonement through political chaos reveals his determination to preserve the path of forgiveness — a determination finally and permanently expressed in Christ's resurrection. Death could not end the priestly work of the one who 'always lives to make intercession for them' (Heb 7:25), because his priesthood rests on an indestructible life rather than on political stability.</p>",
    "53": "<p>Zadok his son, Ahimaaz his son — the recapitulation ends at the monarchy's beginning. The Davidic moment: Zadokite priest serving alongside Davidic king. This convergence of priestly and royal functions in the Davidic monarchy is the OT's high-water mark for the combination Christ permanently embodies. Ahimaaz, who brought David news of Absalom's defeat, is the son of the priest who served the king. In Christ, the Son who brings news of the ultimate victory — resurrection over death — serves the Father who sent him and at whose right hand he now reigns.</p>",
    "54": "<p>The 48 Levitical cities distributed across Israel. A shadow: the territorial distribution of worship personnel across the land reflects YHWH's vision of a covenant community permeated by his presence throughout its entire extent. In Christ, this is transcended and universalized: 'Do you not know that you are God's temple and that God's Spirit dwells in you?' (1 Cor 3:16). The temple is no longer a location but a people; the Levitical city network is the territorial shadow of the church scattered throughout all the nations as the dwelling of the divine presence.</p>",
    "55": "<p>Hebron in Judah — Abraham's burial place, David's first capital, the site of David's anointing. Its assignment to Aaron's sons layers priestly functions onto the founding covenantal geography. A shadow: the places where Abraham received promises and David was anointed become stations of the atonement ministry. In Christ, the promises given to Abraham and the throne promised to David converge in the one who is both 'the son of Abraham' and 'the son of David' (Matt 1:1), fulfilling both the Abrahamic and Davidic covenants in his own person.</p>",
    "56": "<p>The fields around Hebron remained with Caleb because of his faithfulness. A theme: in the Levitical land arrangement, the worshipers of YHWH (Levites) and faithful leaders of Israel (Caleb) share the same geography with defined but complementary portions. In Christ, believers are 'fellow heirs' (Rom 8:17; Eph 3:6) in the inheritance Christ possesses absolutely and shares with those united to him. The Caleb-Levite arrangement at Hebron is a territorial analogy of this shared-yet-distinct inheritance in Christ.</p>",
    "57": "<p>The cities of refuge assigned to Aaron's sons — one of the chapter's richest types. The manslayer who fled was protected until the death of the high priest, after which blood-guilt was removed (Num 35:25-28). As a type: Christ is simultaneously the city of refuge and the high priest whose death releases those who flee to him. Heb 6:18 applies the refuge language directly: 'we who have fled for refuge might have strong encouragement to hold fast to the hope set before us.' The Aaronic city of refuge required both a place to flee to and a priest whose death secured release — Christ is both the place and the priest whose one death accomplishes what the high priest's death only symbolized.</p>",
    "58": "<p>Hilen and Debir with their pasturelands — the legally protected <em>migrāš</em> around each Levitical city. A revelation of God: YHWH provides for those set apart for his service with defined legal protections, not merely spiritual encouragement. The NT develops this: 'the Lord commanded that those who proclaim the gospel should get their living by the gospel' (1 Cor 9:14). The material provision for worship personnel — codified in Levitical law — is a divine ordinance that the NT extends as a principle for those who serve Christ's new-covenant community.</p>",
    "59": "<p>Ashan and Beth-shemesh — Beth-shemesh received the returned ark from Philistia (1 Sam 6:9-12); now it is a Levitical city. A shadow: the place where YHWH's presence returned from enemy territory becomes a station of his worship community. In Christ, the greater return — resurrection from the territory of death — transforms not a single city but the whole world into the potential dwelling of divine presence: 'behold, the dwelling place of God is with man' (Rev 21:3). The ark's return to Beth-shemesh is a local, temporal sign of the universal, permanent return of divine presence in Christ.</p>",
    "60": "<p>Anathoth in Benjamin — Jeremiah's hometown. The prophet who announced the new covenant (Jer 31:31-34) was raised in a Levitical city. A revelation of God: the announcement of the covenant that replaces the Levitical system came from within the Levitical community. Christ similarly came from within Israel's covenant community to fulfill what it pointed toward: 'I have not come to abolish [the Law and the Prophets] but to fulfill them' (Matt 5:17). The new-covenant prophet arises from the covenant community he will transform.</p>",
    "61": "<p>Broader Kohathite families received cities from Manasseh. A theme: the Levitical city network extended beyond the priestly heartland into the central and northern territories. The reach of worship infrastructure into Manasseh reflects YHWH's claim over the entire land. In Christ, the reach extends further: 'you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the end of the earth' (Acts 1:8). The expanding circles of Levitical presence anticipate the expanding circles of gospel witness from Jerusalem to the world.</p>",
    "62": "<p>The Gershomites received cities from Issachar, Asher, Naphtali, and Manasseh in Bashan — all northern territories. A shadow: Levitical presence in the north anticipates the gospel's northward expansion. Isaiah's prophecy of 'a great light' in 'Galilee of the nations' (Isa 9:1-2) covers exactly this territory of Gershomite Levitical cities. When Jesus begins his ministry in Capernaum (Matt 4:13-16), Matthew explicitly quotes Isa 9 — Christ brings the light that the Levitical city network imperfectly anticipated.</p>",
    "63": "<p>The Merarites received cities from Reuben, Gad, and Zebulun — Transjordan and Galilee. A revelation of God: YHWH's worship community is planted across the full territorial extent of the covenant land, including the most geographically marginal territories. This geographic comprehensiveness is the OT form of the NT's insistence that the gospel is 'for everyone who believes' (Rom 1:16), with no geographic exclusion zone. The Merarite cities at the territorial margins represent the farthest reach of the covenant community's presence — the form of what Christ's commission makes universal.</p>",
    "64": "<p>The Israelites gave the Levites these cities — a collective act of the whole covenant community. A theme: the support of those who minister is a community responsibility, not a private arrangement. The same principle governs Paul's instruction that congregations support those who proclaim the gospel (1 Cor 9:14; Gal 6:6; 1 Tim 5:17-18). The Levitical city provision is the institutional precursor to the NT pattern of communal support for ministry, grounded in the same principle: those who serve the community of God's worship deserve the community's material support.</p>",
    "65": "<p>They designated by lot — the lot expressing divine governance over territorial allocation. A revelation of God: the distribution of worship resources is placed under divine direction rather than human favoritism. In the NT, the same principle governs the distribution of spiritual gifts: 'the Spirit apportions to each one individually as he wills' (1 Cor 12:11). The lot for Levitical cities and the Spirit's apportionment of gifts are both expressions of divine sovereignty ensuring the right provision reaches the right people for the worship and service of God.</p>",
    "66": "<p>Kohathite families received cities from Ephraim including Shechem — the great covenant assembly site. A shadow: Kohathite Levites at Shechem place the worship community at the site of Joshua's covenant renewal (Josh 24). In Christ, the covenant assembly site is no longer a geographic location but a person: 'where two or three are gathered in my name, there am I among them' (Matt 18:20). The Shechem assembly-principle migrates from territory to person; the covenant convener is no longer a place but Christ himself.</p>",
    "67": "<p>Shechem in the hill country of Ephraim was a city of refuge — another direct type of Christ. Heb 6:18 applies the refuge language explicitly: 'we who have fled for refuge might have strong encouragement to hold fast to the hope set before us.' Shechem was also where Jacob buried the foreign gods (Gen 35:2-4) and where Joshua gathered all Israel for covenant renewal (Josh 24:25-27). The city of refuge at the site of covenant-making concentrates the shadow: in Christ, the covenant and the refuge are the same — 'the new covenant in my blood' (Luke 22:20) is simultaneously the covenant that binds and the blood that protects those who flee.</p>",
    "68": "<p>Jokmeam and Beth-horon — Beth-horon, where Joshua won his victory with the sun and moon standing still (Josh 10:10-11), becomes a Kohathite Levitical city. A revelation of God: YHWH's victory sites become YHWH's worship sites. The same principle operates in the NT: Christ's cross, the site of apparent defeat that was the ultimate victory, becomes the center of Christian worship — 'we preach Christ crucified... the power of God and the wisdom of God' (1 Cor 1:23-24). The battle site becomes the sanctuary; the instrument of death becomes the locus of eternal life.</p>",
    "69": "<p>Aijalon and Gath-rimmon — Aijalon, where the sun and moon stood still (Josh 10:12-13), becomes a Kohathite Levitical city. A revelation of God: the miracle site is incorporated into the worship community's geography. As the miracle testified to YHWH's control over creation in service of his covenant purposes, the Levitical city in the same location testifies to the same God's ongoing presence with his people. In Christ, the one through whom 'all things were created' (Col 1:16) rose from the dead — the ultimate miracle that becomes the permanent center of worship.</p>",
    "70": "<p>Aner and Bileam from Manasseh — the Kohathite network extends into west Manasseh. A theme: the Levitical city distribution follows no pattern of prestige; obscure cities receive Levitical stations alongside famous ones. This honors the service of communities that will never be center-stage. In Christ, the same principle: 'God chose what is foolish in the world to shame the wise; God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong' (1 Cor 1:27). Bileam is the covenant community's Levitical city; Christ comes from Nazareth.</p>",
    "71": "<p>Golan in Bashan and Ashtaroth — Golan is a city of refuge; Ashtaroth was the capital of Og king of Bashan (Deut 1:4), one of Israel's most formidable conquest targets. The conversion of an Amorite royal capital into a Gershomite Levitical city expresses the claim that YHWH's victory over pagan kingship translates into his community's sustained presence in the land. As a shadow: Christ's victory over death — the ultimate enemy king — translates into the church's sustained presence as 'the body of Christ' in the world (1 Cor 12:27).</p>",
    "72": "<p>Kedesh and Daberath in Issachar — Daberath at the foot of Mount Tabor, site of Deborah's victory and the traditional Transfiguration location (Matt 17:1-8). A shadow: the mountain where Deborah and Barak received YHWH's battle-command stood near a Levitical city; at the same mountain the Father declared 'This is my beloved Son; listen to him' (Mark 9:7). The geography of covenant command becomes the geography of christological revelation — the place where YHWH directed his people in battle becomes the place where he identifies the one to whom all obedience is now directed.</p>",
    "73": "<p>Ramoth and Anem in Issachar — the Gershomite network covers the Jezreel Valley broadly. A revelation of God: the same God who called Levi and appointed Aaron also ensures worship coverage in the agriculturally productive valleys. YHWH's provision for worship is not limited to religiously famous mountains but extends into the plains where ordinary life occurs. In Christ, this comprehensive reach is the basis for the universal mission: 'all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me... make disciples of all nations' (Matt 28:18-19). The Levitical plain-coverage is the OT form of the universal commission.</p>",
    "74": "<p>Mashal and Abdon in Asher — Gershomite cities in the coastal north, Israel's most Phoenician-adjacent zone. A theme: the Levites are placed precisely where the alternative religious systems are strongest. Christ's community follows the same pattern of incarnational placement in hostile territory: 'I am sending you out as lambs in the midst of wolves' (Luke 10:3); 'I do not ask that you take them out of the world, but that you keep them from the evil one' (John 17:15). The Levitical presence in Asher is the OT form of the church's presence in pagan culture.</p>",
    "75": "<p>Hukok and Rehob in Asher — additional Gershomite cities in the northern coastal territory. A revelation of God: he plants his community at the margins, not merely in protected enclaves. In Christ, this principle reaches its fullest expression in the incarnation itself — the Son of God placed at the cultural margin of Roman Palestine, in Galilee of the nations, to reach those farthest from the religious center. 'He came to his own, and his own people did not receive him' (John 1:11) — yet it is precisely from the margins that the universal mission launches (Acts 1:8).</p>",
    "76": "<p>Kedesh in Galilee — a city of refuge in upper Galilee, in the territory Isaiah identified as the place that would 'see a great light' (Isa 9:1-2). A type: the city of refuge stands in the same territory where Christ begins his ministry of refuge-for-sinners (Matt 4:13-16, where Matthew explicitly quotes Isa 9). The physical protection offered by the Galilean city of refuge (Kedesh) is the institutional shadow of the spiritual protection Christ offers in the same geographic region: 'Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest' (Matt 11:28).</p>",
    "77": "<p>Rimmono and Tabor in Zebulun — Merarite cities near Mount Tabor. The Merarites bore structural weight; at Tabor, the ultimate weight-bearer is identified: the Father declares 'This is my beloved Son' (Matt 17:5). A revelation of God: the mountain near the Merarite city of structural burden becomes the location where the Son is revealed as the one who bears all things — 'upholding the universe by the word of his power' (Heb 1:3). The Merarite principle of weight-bearing reaches its ultimate expression in the incarnate Son who sustains all creation.</p>",
    "78": "<p>Bezer in the desert and Jahzah — Merarite cities in Reuben's Transjordanian territory. Bezer is a city of refuge east of the Jordan. A theme: YHWH's provision of refuge extends across every boundary — geographic, cultural, tribal. In Christ, this boundary-crossing is complete: 'there is no distinction between Jew and Greek; for the same Lord is Lord of all, bestowing his riches on all who call on him' (Rom 10:12). Bezer in the desert is the OT's Transjordanian form of this boundless provision of refuge.</p>",
    "79": "<p>Kedemoth and Mephaath — Merarite cities in Reuben's territory. Kedemoth was where Moses sent a peaceful message to Sihon before the conquest (Deut 2:26) — the site of failed diplomacy before military victory. A revelation of God: YHWH does not resort to force without first offering peace. The same pattern governs the gospel: 'we implore you on behalf of Christ, be reconciled to God' (2 Cor 5:20). Christ's mission follows this sequence — the gospel of peace proclaimed before the day of judgment. The city at the site of peace-offer becomes a worship station.</p>",
    "80": "<p>Ramoth in Gilead and Mahanaim — Merarite cities with rich historical associations. Mahanaim ('two camps') was where angels met Jacob (Gen 32:1-2) and where David fled during Absalom's revolt (2 Sam 17:24). The 'two camps' name is christologically evocative: divine army alongside human company. In Christ, the 'two camps' meet permanently — divine and human in one person. The site where Jacob saw the heavenly army becomes a Merarite city; the site where divinity and humanity permanently converge is the incarnate Son himself, 'truly God and truly man.'</p>",
    "81": "<p>Heshbon and Jazer — former Amorite strongholds (Num 21:25-32) converted into Merarite Levitical cities. A shadow pointing to the ultimate eschatological reality: the places taken from pagan kings in the conquest become stations of YHWH's worship infrastructure. In Christ, this principle reaches its completion: 'the kingdom of the world has become the kingdom of our Lord and of his Christ, and he shall reign forever and ever' (Rev 11:15). Every Amorite stronghold converted to a Levitical city is a token of the ultimate reality — all things will be 'subjected to him' (1 Cor 15:28), and the full territory of creation will be inhabited by worshipers of the one who made and redeemed it.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', '1chronicles')
    merge_comm(c, CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '1chronicles', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in CHRIST.values())
    print(f'1chronicles mkt-christ ch6: wrote {count} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
